BUG-D5775F3E	bug_d5775f3e	Default provider selection still falls back to arbitrary registry order when no priority match exists	FIXED	P2	P2	registry.provider_execution_registry.default_provider_slug() checks a hardcoded priority list first and then falls back to next(iter(_REGISTRY)) if none of those providers are present. That makes the 	manual	\N	\N	\N		\N	2026-04-16 16:28:06.189026-07	2026-04-17 01:05:20.764925-07	2026-04-16 16:28:06.189026-07	2026-04-17 01:05:20.764925-07	RUNTIME	registry.provider_execution_registry.default_provider_slug() checks a hardcoded priority list first and then falls back to next(iter(_REGISTRY)) if none of those providers are present. That makes the default provider depend on insertion order whenever the live registry contains only non-priority providers, which is a silent authority leak rather than an explicit policy. The code comment already calls out that alphabetical fallback drifted from the operational default lane, but the remaining next(iter(_REGISTRY)) path is still arbitrary and can pick the wrong provider without any error or warning.\n\nWhy it matters: default provider resolution feeds downstream route selection and operator behavior. When the fallback is arbitrary, a newly introduced or partially loaded registry can route traffic to the wrong lane even though the system looks healthy.\n\nEvidence: provider_execution_registry.py at default_provider_slug() uses a fixed _DEFAULT_PROVIDER_PRIORITY loop and then returns next(iter(_REGISTRY)); the same module raises when the registry is empty, so the arbitrary fallback only appears when the registry is non-empty but not covered by the priority list; provider_registry.py and routing code consume the default provider helper as a live authority.\n\nSuspected root cause: the default-selection policy is encoded partly as a priority list and partly as an implicit iteration fallback instead of a single explicit ordered policy.\n\nSuggested next step: replace the implicit iteration fallback with an explicit, DB-backed default provider policy or fail closed when no configured provider matches the priority set.	codex	\N	provider-registry-shim,default-selection,authority	\N	{}	\N
