BUG-01CBAEC0	bug_01cbaec0	Split provider registry authority persists through compatibility shims and legacy import paths	FIXED	P2	P2	The provider execution authority is nominally DB-backed in registry.provider_execution_registry, but the repo still keeps live compatibility facades in adapters/provider_registry.py and registry/provi	manual	\N	\N	\N		\N	2026-04-16 16:25:54.364373-07	2026-04-16 23:32:12.531707-07	2026-04-16 16:25:54.364373-07	2026-04-16 23:32:12.531707-07	ARCHITECTURE	The provider execution authority is nominally DB-backed in registry.provider_execution_registry, but the repo still keeps live compatibility facades in adapters/provider_registry.py and registry/provider_onboarding/_registry.py that re-export the canonical modules while older runtime callers still import the legacy paths. That keeps two API surfaces alive for the same authority and makes drift easy to hide behind import compatibility instead of forcing a single front door. The risk is not cosmetic: runtime behavior, onboarding helpers, and tests can continue to depend on the shim layer and mask divergence in the canonical registry.\n\nWhy it matters: split authority here means future fixes can land in the canonical registry while older callers keep exercising the shim path, so the system can appear stable while semantics diverge.\n\nEvidence: adapters/provider_registry.py is a full re-export facade over registry.provider_execution_registry; registry/provider_onboarding/_registry.py is also a re-export shim over registry.provider_onboarding_repository; chat_orchestrator.py, llm_task.py, mcp_bridge.py, execution_backends.py, and multiple tests still import adapters.provider_registry directly; provider_execution_registry.py itself explicitly documents that the legacy import path should continue using adapters.provider_registry.\n\nSuspected root cause: compatibility layers were retained after the canonical registry became authoritative, but the repo has not finished removing the old import surface or wiring callers exclusively through the canonical module.\n\nSuggested next step: inventory legacy imports of adapters.provider_registry and registry.provider_onboarding._registry, then decide whether to collapse them to the canonical registry or make the shim an explicit compatibility boundary with deprecation and coverage gates.	codex	\N	provider-registry-shim,split-authority	[-0.068561,-0.097847,0.001813,-0.016957,0.045667,-0.045674,-0.039896,0.04214,-0.058076,-0.044372,0.069619,0.041679,0.032748,0.047213,0.092407,0.060107,0.054408,-0.027497,-0.049781,0.102578,-0.050059,-0.079615,-0.037227,0.051126,-0.066042,-0.067615,-0.028392,0.007112,0.034188,-0.035644,0.035065,0.095538,-0.055784,-0.058266,0.008516,0.078073,0.03622,-0.040288,-0.052514,-0.045273,0.094105,0.034942,-0.059022,-0.029094,0.017593,-0.05319,0.047412,-0.01911,-0.019085,-0.086309,0.01335,0.030919,-0.000295,-0.015959,-0.017779,0.050839,0.016809,0.032764,0.014637,0.048729,-0.036648,0.055931,-0.049421,-0.035026,-0.010592,-0.028546,0.010802,-0.041398,0.056712,-0.050092,-0.132582,-0.009467,-0.054403,-0.025486,0.045724,-0.011222,-0.041876,0.006541,-0.030886,-0.172138,0.043013,0.042958,0.008237,0.004073,0.094056,-0.028162,-0.031309,-0.040939,0.031658,0.035724,0.122825,-0.104073,0.143859,0.002076,0.112605,0.043293,-0.013743,0.040178,0.063002,0.056422,-0.007173,-0.077714,-0.076546,0.099395,0.035647,0.019799,-0.064619,-0.021,0.033102,0.007059,0.023879,-0.028871,0.037339,-0.045455,-0.055614,0.038264,-0.030568,0.01184,0.050852,0.014977,-0.049198,-0.018543,0.165741,-0.028677,0.101571,0.055855,-0.018851,0,-0.070655,0.018538,-0.027878,0.015773,0.038256,-0.002103,-0.003391,0.05341,-0.01044,-0.029943,-0.031604,0.047076,-0.051227,-0.010526,0.132246,0.024728,-0.031508,0.078794,0.057392,0.059039,-0.022032,0.049941,-0.003634,-0.018691,0.074102,-0.00669,0.015497,0.014491,-0.004714,0.022587,-0.044359,-0.012451,0.040175,0.056178,0.045862,0.050508,-0.043376,-0.102335,-0.069365,-0.045709,-0.03261,0.0197,-0.025482,0.0113