BUG-052652D3	bug_052652d3	Sticky CLI chat route bypasses tool-capable HTTP routing once last-good CLI is prioritized	FIXED	P1	P1	ChatOrchestrator._resolve_route_chain() reorders routes through _prioritize_last_good_cli_route(), and send_message()/send_message_streaming() immediately take the CLI fast path whenever routes[0].ada	manual	\N	\N	\N		\N	2026-04-16 16:28:06.192862-07	2026-04-17 01:01:10.664604-07	2026-04-16 16:28:06.192862-07	2026-04-17 01:01:10.664604-07	WIRING	ChatOrchestrator._resolve_route_chain() reorders routes through _prioritize_last_good_cli_route(), and send_message()/send_message_streaming() immediately take the CLI fast path whenever routes[0].adapter_type == 'cli_llm'. That means a previously successful CLI route can become the permanent first choice and bypass the HTTP tool loop entirely, even though the same conversation runtime otherwise supports tool execution only in the HTTP branch. The behavior is hidden behind route-ordering rather than an explicit capability check, so tool-capable conversations can silently lose tool access depending on which lane happened to work last.\n\nWhy it matters: this is a runtime wiring bug, not just preference logic. The branch choice changes whether the assistant can call tools at all. A healthy CLI lane can therefore suppress a more capable HTTP lane and make the system look functional while degrading behavior under the hood.\n\nEvidence: chat_orchestrator.py checks only the first resolved route before choosing CLI vs HTTP; _prioritize_last_good_cli_route() moves the last successful CLI route to the front if present; the CLI path never enters the tool-call loop, while the HTTP path does; _resolve_model() only finds the first HTTP-backed route after that ordering has already been skewed.\n\nSuspected root cause: route preference and execution capability are coupled through list ordering instead of explicit capability selection, so a cache of prior CLI success can override tool availability.\n\nSuggested next step: separate preferred route from tool-capable route and require an explicit capability gate before short-circuiting into the CLI path.	codex	\N	chat-routing,tool-capability,route-ordering	\N	{}	\N
