BUG-58D022F0	bug_58d022f0	Bug/query entrypoints inherit schema bootstrap and registry sync side effects from get_pg_conn	FIXED	P2	P2	Concrete manifestation: `_BaseSubsystems.get_pg_conn()` does not just hand out a connection; it also calls `ensure_postgres_available()`, bootstraps workflow schema, runs registry sync, and may trigge	manual	\N	\N	\N		\N	2026-04-16 12:34:55.563638-07	2026-04-16 14:07:55.385942-07	2026-04-16 12:34:55.563638-07	2026-04-16 14:08:46.544435-07	WIRING	Concrete manifestation: `_BaseSubsystems.get_pg_conn()` does not just hand out a connection; it also calls `ensure_postgres_available()`, bootstraps workflow schema, runs registry sync, and may trigger startup wiring before returning. That means a simple bug or query path can fail in unrelated bootstrap or registry code and surface as a generic authority problem even when the bug tracker insert path itself is fine. Evidence: `_BaseSubsystems.get_pg_conn()`, `create_pg_conn()`, `ensure_postgres_available()`, and the `sync_registries()` call inside `get_pg_conn()`. Next step: separate connection acquisition from bootstrapping and make startup side effects explicit instead of implicit.	codex	\N		[-0.099792,-0.089731,-0.043097,0.06066,-0.010559,-0.038519,-0.016116,0.00393,-0.081226,-0.054343,-0.008074,0.031932,0.009063,-0.049464,0.013371,0.055483,0.099898,-0.027964,0.017775,0.041468,-0.111915,-0.040349,-0.08118,0.064144,-0.073705,-0.100966,-0.062137,0.022169,0.058029,0.007139,-0.031615,0.070065,-0.085704,0.029657,0.065754,0.111153,0.082916,-0.021804,-0.05374,-0.027437,0.142877,0.01545,-0.00464,0.047497,0.0066,-0.082325,0.020321,-0.026923,-0.06954,-0.065295,-0.04772,-0.016402,0.062697,-0.037799,-0.02425,0.109141,0.013231,0.044463,0.034116,0.052209,0.029979,0.003662,-0.077019,-0.022125,-0.007918,0.024249,0.058178,-0.047355,0.067417,0.021298,0.000937,0.041856,-0.108396,0.053273,-0.049065,0.143017,-0.028912,0.025783,-0.000366,-0.157448,-0.040335,0.050864,0.001411,0.031123,0.03009,-0.034923,0.012153,-0.