BUG-40428B38	bug_40428b38	Split queue admission authority: health gate and runtime submission enforce the same queue rule in different modules	FIXED	P2	P2	Queue admission is enforced in two different places with two different shapes: runtime submission uses runtime/workflow/_admission.py::_enforce_queue_admission() and its local _queue_depth_from_workfl	manual	\N	\N	\N	cluster.queue_admission_authority.2026-04-16	\N	2026-04-16 20:59:39.474826-07	2026-04-16 23:08:09.394939-07	2026-04-16 20:59:39.474826-07	2026-04-16 23:08:09.394939-07	ARCHITECTURE	Queue admission is enforced in two different places with two different shapes: runtime submission uses runtime/workflow/_admission.py::_enforce_queue_admission() and its local _queue_depth_from_workflow_jobs() helper, while runtime/health.py defines a separate QueueAdmissionGate plus QueueDepthProbe. The health gate is not the submission authority, and the submission authority does not reuse the health gate, so the same queue pressure can be measured and rejected through parallel logic that can drift. This is a structural split of authority, not just a duplicate query. It matters because queue pressure, warning thresholds, and rejection behavior can diverge silently, leaving operators with health signals that do not match the real dispatch path. Evidence: runtime/health.py:566-759 defines QueueDepthProbe, AdmissionDecision, QueueAdmissionGate, and queue_admission_check; runtime/workflow/_admission.py:116-154 defines _queue_depth_from_workflow_jobs() and _enforce_queue_admission(); runtime/workflow/_admission.py:1169 and runtime/workflow/_status.py:1015 call the runtime-side enforcement, not the health-side gate. Suggested next step: collapse queue admission into one shared authority and have both health reporting and submission call that single implementation.	codex	\N	cluster:queue-admission,authority-split,runtime,health	[-0.071901,-0.036175,-0.02424,-0.028396,-0.012726,-0.131342,0.021709,-0.034483,0.059294,-0.042471,0.00