BUG-971B57EC	bug_971b57ec	Bug packet tests miss the real untagged manual filing path and only prove synthetic signatures	FIXED	P3	P3	Test drift: the packet/replay unit tests mostly monkeypatch `failure_packet()` to return invented fingerprints such as `fp-alpha` and `fp-fallback`, while the historical-fixes coverage exercises expli	manual	\N	\N	\N		\N	2026-04-16 14:17:31.477873-07	2026-04-16 14:31:37.430748-07	2026-04-16 14:17:31.477873-07	2026-04-16 14:31:48.386834-07	TEST	Test drift: the packet/replay unit tests mostly monkeypatch `failure_packet()` to return invented fingerprints such as `fp-alpha` and `fp-fallback`, while the historical-fixes coverage exercises explicitly tagged bugs. That means the suite proves the downstream consumers behave when a packet already contains a strong signature, but it never exercises the real boundary where a plain manual bug is filed with no receipt evidence or signature tags. Live runtime evidence shows the gap matters: multiple unrelated manual bugs currently produce the same fallback fingerprint and `insufficient_signature` history/backfill reasons, but the test suite still passes. Evidence in tests: Code&DBs/Workflow/tests/unit/test_bug_tracker.py lines around 854-959 monkeypatch packet fingerprints, and lines around 1181-1190 validate historical fixes only after explicit failure-code/node tags are present. Impact: test coverage validates the happy path and hides the production failure mode where manual bugs cannot participate in replay/backfill identity. Related files: Code&DBs/Workflow/tests/unit/test_bug_tracker.py, Code&DBs/Workflow/runtime/bug_tracker.py.	codex	\N		[-0.126393,0.013783,0.02051,-0.015956,0.094531,-0.062668,-0.017236,0.021322,-0.130091,0.02227,0.05684,0.024952,0.029694,-0.010235,-0.01037,-0.085615,0.022067,-0.034128,0.057135,-0.015176,-0.099709,0.013016,0.034807,0.018365,-0.061072,0.003987,-0.042437,0.020513,0.014269,-0.06586,0.024911,0.121996,-0.088022,0.019943,0.12606,0.014175,0.05361,0.026296,0.03988,0.