BUG-84559B90	bug_84559b90	Sync Postgres pool lifecycle still depends on wrapper close instead of an explicit shutdown contract	OPEN	P2	P2	storage/postgres/connection.py has a singleton asyncpg pool plus a background bridge loop, but the lifecycle is still only partially modeled. get_workflow_pool() caches the pool globally, SyncPostgres	manual	\N	\N	\N	cluster.pool_lifecycle.2026-04-16	\N	2026-04-16 20:59:50.124848-07	\N	2026-04-16 20:59:50.124848-07	2026-04-16 20:59:50.124848-07	RUNTIME	storage/postgres/connection.py has a singleton asyncpg pool plus a background bridge loop, but the lifecycle is still only partially modeled. get_workflow_pool() caches the pool globally, SyncPostgresConnection.close() delegates to shutdown_workflow_pool(), and shutdown_workflow_pool() is the only explicit teardown path. That means any caller that reuses the wrapper without owning the process lifecycle can leave the bridge loop and cached pool as hidden process state. The code also still has to compare DSNs manually in get_workflow_pool() to avoid reusing a pool across different WORKFLOW_DATABASE_URL values. This is a runtime state-management smell, not a style nit: pool identity, DSN identity, and shutdown are split across globals and wrapper methods. Evidence: storage/postgres/connection.py:19-24 declares _workflow_pool and _workflow_pool_dsn globals; storage/postgres/connection.py:155-167 reopens the pool on DSN mismatch; storage/postgres/connection.py:169-189 defines shutdown_workflow_pool() and stops the bridge loop; storage/postgres/connection.py:221-224 makes SyncPostgresConnection.close() call shutdown_workflow_pool(). Suggested next step: make pool ownership explicit at the process boundary and ensure callers that create shared connections do not accidentally own global teardown semantics.	codex	\N	cluster:connection-lifecycle,runtime,state-management	[-0.124488,-0.015414,-0.019463,0.033719,-0.035269,-0.073736,0.029807,-0.022563,0.055872,-0.050787,-0.075707,0.128149,-0.0757