BUG-5FE75927	bug_5fe75927	Startup registry sync failures are swallowed and then discarded by get_pg_conn	WONT_FIX	P2	P2	`surfaces._boot.sync_registries()` catches `Exception` around four independent sync steps, records them only in a local `skipped` list, and `_BaseSubsystems.get_pg_conn()` ignores the returned `(succe	manual	\N	\N	\N		\N	2026-04-16 12:38:07.677416-07	2026-04-16 13:40:55.219636-07	2026-04-16 12:38:07.677416-07	2026-04-16 13:40:55.219636-07	RUNTIME	`surfaces._boot.sync_registries()` catches `Exception` around four independent sync steps, records them only in a local `skipped` list, and `_BaseSubsystems.get_pg_conn()` ignores the returned `(succeeded, skipped)` tuple entirely. That means a broken integration registry, capability catalog, runtime profile sync, or reference catalog seeder can fail during startup with no surfaced error or durable record, leaving the process running against partial authority state. Evidence: `surfaces/_boot.py:47-76` and `_subsystems_base.py:133-142`. Next step: fail or at least emit a structured warning when critical startup syncs are skipped, and route the skipped list into observability so operators can query it.	codex	\N		[-0.097244,-0.054709,-0.007486,0.013206,0.049395,-0.062404,-0.0297,0.014331,-0.115756,-0.045431,0.023053,0.062756,0.023854,-0.023977,-0.009156,0.019046,0.050451,-0.011602,0.020932,0.032677,-0.115904,0.022229,-0.025069,0.096914,-0.07284,-0.06114,-0.04913,-0.009088,0.016761,0.025439,-0.015483,0.023394,-0.026726,0.062176,0.113873,0.080318,0.0193,-0.047867,-0.005614,-0.029958,0.129124,0.018633,-0.062685,0.070148,-0.007226,0.008558,0.006189,-0.031667,-0.015469,-0.077865,-0.043352,0.02607,0.055428,-0.068831,0.009562,0.077252,-0.004933,0.012681,0.052505,0.038685,0.009318,-0.005195,-0.081901,-0.01056,0.034315,0.053826,0.048669,-0.008561,0.055867,0.072245,-0.00559,0.037329,-0.065047,0.082214,-0.053425,0.075267,0.019278,-0.078273,-0.076571,-0.136739,-0.113017,-0.018807,0.008601,0.013655,-0.017595,-0.067219,-0.