BUG-12ABA261	bug_12aba261	Queue health warnings and runtime rejection use different thresholds and status signals, so operators can see green health while admission is already failing	FIXED	P2	P2	QueueDepthProbe in runtime/health.py reports warning and critical states from one counting rule, while QueueAdmissionGate in the same module and _enforce_queue_admission() in runtime/workflow/_admissi	manual	\N	\N	\N	cluster.queue_admission_authority.2026-04-16	\N	2026-04-16 20:59:50.134872-07	2026-04-16 23:08:22.717132-07	2026-04-16 20:59:50.134872-07	2026-04-16 23:08:22.717132-07	VERIFY	QueueDepthProbe in runtime/health.py reports warning and critical states from one counting rule, while QueueAdmissionGate in the same module and _enforce_queue_admission() in runtime/workflow/_admission.py enforce a separate projected-depth rule against the same workflow_jobs table. The health probe also reports claimed and running counts, but its admission helper only checks pending+ready, and the runtime submission path uses its own count helper and threshold logic. That means health can expose a queue state that looks merely warning or healthy while the actual submit path is already rejecting jobs, or vice versa, depending on how those thresholds are tuned. This is an observability drift bug because the reported queue signal is not the same signal the runtime uses to make admission decisions. Evidence: runtime/health.py:566-679 computes queue probe status and details; runtime/health.py:686-759 defines a separate admission gate; runtime/workflow/_admission.py:116-154 and runtime/workflow/_status.py:1015 use runtime-side enforcement instead of the health gate; queue probe and gate are not sharing a single authoritative result type. Suggested next step: define one queue admission result model and have health rendering, dispatch admission, and status surfaces consume it consistently.	codex	\N	cluster:queue-admission,observability,verify,runtime	[-0.021844,-0.008913,-0.037538,0.028134,0.0599